     SECTION 2
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2>SECTION 2 | MAJOR INTRODUCTION &amp; HIGHLIGHTS</h2>
<p style="font-size:9pt;color:#666;font-style:italic;">This content appears on Page 1 of the Major Map. Write for a prospective or first-year student audience — be compelling, clear, and specific to NC A&amp;T.</p>

<h3>Bold Tagline / Value Statement</h3>
<div class="bold-tagline">
Landscape architects design the places where life happens — from urban parks and green infrastructure to climate-resilient communities. NC A&amp;T's BSLA is the only LAAB-accredited landscape architecture program at a public HBCU, preparing students to lead in environmental justice, sustainable design, and equitable placemaking.
</div>

<h3>Program Description</h3>
<p>The Bachelor of Science in Landscape Architecture at NC A&amp;T is a rigorous, studio-intensive professional degree accredited by the Landscape Architectural Accreditation Board (LAAB). Across four years, students progress through a sequenced curriculum of 24 LDAR courses that build competencies in design fundamentals, ecological systems, site engineering, construction documentation, and collaborative professional practice. The program integrates community-engaged design with technical mastery, producing graduates who are eligible for the Landscape Architect Registration Examination (LARE) and prepared for immediate professional contribution. As the only LAAB-accredited program at a public HBCU, NC A&amp;T uniquely positions graduates to bring underrepresented perspectives to environmental design, green infrastructure, and community-centered planning.</p>

<h3>Program Highlights (6 bullet points)</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>LAAB Accredited</b> — One of only ~70 accredited landscape architecture programs in the U.S., and the only one at a public HBCU</li>
<li><b>24-Course Professional Studio Sequence</b> — Intensive design studios every semester from Year 1 through Capstone, with dedicated studios for Social Systems (LDAR 247), Ecological Systems (LDAR 248), Stormwater/Landform (LDAR 347), Master Planning (LDAR 348), Collaborative (LDAR 447), and Capstone (LDAR 448)</li>
<li><b>LARE Exam Pathway</b> — Curriculum mapped directly to all 4 sections of the Landscape Architect Registration Examination; LDAR 442 (Design in Practice) includes structured LARE prep</li>
<li><b>Required Professional Internship</b> — LDAR 400 provides credit for internship at landscape architecture firms, public agencies, or allied design practices (can be taken any summer)</li>
<li><b>Community-Engaged Design Focus</b> — Students work with real communities in Greensboro and the Piedmont Triad on participatory design projects addressing environmental justice and equitable access to green space</li>
<li><b>GIS &amp; Digital Technology</b> — Advanced geospatial analysis (LDAR 349), CAD/BIM pipeline (LDAR 170/171), and construction documentation (LDAR 249) ensure graduates are technically proficient on day one</li>
</ul>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 3 — PAGE BREAK
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="page-break"></div>
<h2>SECTION 3 | CAREERS &amp; GRADUATE PATHWAYS</h2>

<h3>Common Job Titles for Graduates</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:100%;" colspan="2">
1. Landscape Architect (Licensed, after LARE passage)<br>
2. Landscape Designer<br>
3. Urban Designer / Urban Planner<br>
4. Environmental Planner<br>
5. Green Infrastructure Specialist<br>
6. Park Planner / Recreation Facility Designer<br>
7. Site Development Project Manager<br>
8. Stormwater Management Designer<br>
9. Land Use / Environmental Consultant<br>
10. Campus / Institutional Planner
</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Common Employers &amp; Industries</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:100%;" colspan="2">
1. <b>Landscape Architecture Firms</b> — Design Workshop, AECOM, Sasaki, SWA Group, Hood Design Studio, Smith Dalia<br>
2. <b>Civil/Environmental Engineering Firms</b> — Kimley-Horn, WSP, Stantec, Terracon<br>
3. <b>Federal Government</b> — National Park Service, USDA NRCS, Army Corps of Engineers, GSA<br>
4. <b>State &amp; Local Government</b> — NC DOT, city parks &amp; recreation departments, county planning offices<br>
5. <b>Nonprofit / NGO</b> — The Trust for Public Land, The Nature Conservancy, local land conservancies<br>
6. <b>Real Estate Development</b> — mixed-use developers, resort/hospitality design teams<br>
7. <b>Architecture &amp; Multidisciplinary Firms</b> — Perkins&amp;Will, Gensler, SmithGroup<br>
8. <b>Academic / Research Institutions</b> — university facilities planning, extension services
</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Graduate &amp; Professional School Pathways</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:100%;" colspan="2">
• Master of Landscape Architecture (MLA) — advanced research/design studios<br>
• Master of Urban Design (MUD) — urban-scale design and policy<br>
• Master of City and Regional Planning (MCRP)<br>
• Master of Environmental Management (MEM)<br>
• Ph.D. in Landscape Architecture, Environmental Design, or Planning<br>
• Master of Architecture (M.Arch) — dual-degree pathway<br>
• NC A&amp;T does not currently offer an accelerated 4+1 in LA; students pursue MLA at peer institutions (e.g., NC State, UVA, Penn, Harvard GSD, Morgan State)
</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Licensure / Certifications Required</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:100%;" colspan="2">
• <b>LARE (Landscape Architect Registration Examination)</b> — Required for licensure in all 50 states. 4-section exam administered by CLARB. NC A&amp;T's curriculum maps to all 4 sections. Graduates are eligible to begin testing upon degree completion (varies by state).<br>
• <b>CLARB Certification</b> — Council of Landscape Architectural Registration Boards credential facilitating multi-state licensure reciprocity<br>
• <b>LEED AP (Optional)</b> — Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design Accredited Professional; valued in sustainable design practice<br>
• <b>ISA Certified Arborist (Optional)</b> — International Society of Arboriculture certification for tree care and urban forestry specialization
</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 4 — PAGE BREAK
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="page-break"></div>
<h2>SECTION 4 | EXPERIENTIAL LEARNING BY ACADEMIC YEAR</h2>
<p style="font-size:9pt;color:#666;font-style:italic;">For each of the four themes below, list specific activities, programs, events, courses, organizations, and resources that students in YOUR major should engage with during each academic year.</p>

<!-- THEME 1: PURPOSE -->
<h3><span class="section-emoji">🔍</span> Discover &amp; Demonstrate Purpose | Connecting passion to purpose</h3>
<table class="grid-table">
<tr>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 1 – Explore</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 2 – Engage</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 3 – Develop</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 4 – Launch</th>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 103</b> — Landscape Architecture Discovery: Survey profession scope, ethics, career pathways; field visits to Greensboro firms and public agencies<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 147</b> — Design Foundations Studio: Develop spatial reasoning, compositional awareness, and design process fluency<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 148</b> — LA Fundamentals: Site inventory, analysis, and preliminary design on real Piedmont sites<br><br>
    Attend CAES First-Year Discovery Seminar
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 255</b> — Design Theory: Read primary texts in phenomenology, ecology, and resilience theory; develop written design philosophy statements<br><br>
    Attend ASLA regional conference or CELA symposium as a student observer<br><br>
    Participate in a design competition (e.g., ASLA Student Awards, SLLA Design Challenge)
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 349</b> — GIS Applications in Environmental Design: LIDAR, suitability modeling, environmental impact analysis using real geospatial datasets<br><br>
    Apply for CUGR (Center for Undergraduate Research) faculty mentorship for design-research project<br><br>
    Develop independent research question for potential capstone topic
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 440</b> — Design Proposal Writing: Write RFQ/RFP responses, grant proposals, and competition narratives using professional evaluation criteria<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 448</b> — Capstone Project Studio: Self-directed design-research project assessed by faculty jury and external professional reviewers<br><br>
    Present capstone work at CAES Research Forum or ASLA student poster session
  </td>
</tr>
</table>

<!-- THEME 2: COMMUNITIES -->
<h3><span class="section-emoji">🤝</span> Cultivate Your Communities | Building belonging and networks</h3>
<table class="grid-table">
<tr>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 1 – Explore</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 2 – Engage</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 3 – Develop</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 4 – Launch</th>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>
    Join <b>ASLA Student Chapter</b> (American Society of Landscape Architects) — attend first meeting during Welcome Week<br><br>
    Attend CAES Welcome Back cookout and department mixers<br><br>
    Engage with <b>NOMA</b> student chapter (National Organization of Minority Architects)<br><br>
    Connect with SGA, Greek life, and university-wide student organizations
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 247</b> — Social Systems Studio: Partner with underserved Greensboro neighborhoods for participatory co-design, community workshops, and design charrettes<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 204</b> — Plant Materials: Weekly plant walks with cohort; plant ID practicum builds community through shared field experience<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 244</b> — Designing with Plants: Collaborative planting design projects for community gardens and urban streetscapes<br><br>
    Volunteer with Greensboro Beautiful, local Habitat for Humanity builds, or community garden initiatives
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 348</b> — Master Planning / Field Study Studio: Stakeholder interviews, community engagement, and comprehensive master plans for campus or community sites<br><br>
    Mentor incoming Year 1 and Year 2 students through ASLA chapter or departmental peer mentoring program<br><br>
    Participate in NC A&amp;T Community Design Charrettes or AIAS/ASLA joint events
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 447</b> — The Collaborative Studio: Cross-disciplinary teams with architecture, engineering, and planning students addressing complex real-world projects<br><br>
    Serve as ASLA Student Chapter officer; organize firm visits, alumni panels, and portfolio review nights<br><br>
    Build professional network through alumni mentorship and CLARB Council connections
  </td>
</tr>
</table>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<!-- THEME 3: LOCAL & GLOBAL -->
<h3><span class="section-emoji">🌍</span> Engage Locally &amp; Globally | Applying knowledge beyond campus</h3>
<table class="grid-table">
<tr>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 1 – Explore</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 2 – Engage</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 3 – Develop</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 4 – Launch</th>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 104</b> — LA History: Global survey from Mesopotamian gardens through Olmsted to contemporary ecological design; attention to underrepresented voices<br><br>
    Explore Greensboro's parks, greenways, and public spaces through guided field trips (Downtown Greenway, Bicentennial Garden, Hester Park)<br><br>
    Begin exploring Study Abroad options through NC A&amp;T International Programs office
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 248</b> — Ecological Systems Studio: Watershed management, habitat restoration, green infrastructure at landscape scale; stream corridor restoration and urban heat island mitigation<br><br>
    Participate in National Landscape Architecture Month (April) service projects<br><br>
    Explore study abroad partnerships (e.g., summer programs in Italy, Scandinavia, or Caribbean sustainability studios)
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 345</b> — Site Systems: ADA-compliant grading, utility coordination, stormwater infrastructure applied to real Piedmont development sites<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 347</b> — Landform &amp; Stormwater Studio: Bioretention systems, constructed wetlands, permeable paving — regulatory compliance and engineering calculations<br><br>
    Participate in study abroad or domestic field study component of LDAR 348<br><br>
    Apply for international design workshops or LAF fellowship opportunities
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 455</b> — Current Issues and Topics in LA: Climate adaptation, environmental justice, indigenous land stewardship, post-disaster recovery design; visiting practitioners and virtual conferences<br><br>
    Engage with professional practice at regional and national scale through internship network and capstone research<br><br>
    Connect capstone research to regional environmental justice priorities in the Piedmont Triad
  </td>
</tr>
</table>

<!-- THEME 4: PROFESSIONAL IDENTITY -->
<h3><span class="section-emoji">💼</span> Develop Professional Identity | Building career readiness and credentials</h3>
<table class="grid-table">
<tr>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 1 – Explore</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 2 – Engage</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 3 – Develop</th>
  <th style="width:25%;">Year 4 – Launch</th>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 170</b> — LA Graphics I: Freehand sketching, orthographic drawing, digital drafting; portfolio-quality deliverables from first assignment<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 171</b> — LA Graphics II: CAD, Adobe Creative Suite, 3D modeling; professional-standard plan graphics, sections, and perspectives<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 181</b> — Materials and Construction: Material properties, construction assemblies, detailing, specification writing<br><br>
    Create Handshake profile; attend Career Services orientation
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 249</b> — Construction Documents: Complete CD sets (layout, grading, planting, detail sheets, specs) at industry standard — the "Billable on Day One" benchmark<br><br>
    Register for Handshake and attend CAES Career Fair<br><br>
    Build initial project portfolio from Year 1–2 studio work; attend Career Services resume workshop<br><br>
    Identify potential internship firms; conduct informational interviews<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 400</b> — Internship Independent Study: Can be registered as early as sophomore summer when students secure a position
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 349</b> — GIS Applications: Advanced digital proficiency in ArcGIS, LIDAR processing, suitability modeling<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 347</b> — Landform &amp; Stormwater Studio: Technical competency directly mapped to LARE Section 4<br><br>
    Attend ASLA Annual Conference or state chapter conference; present student work<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 400</b> — Internship can also be taken this summer<br><br>
    Attend Professional Development headshot and business attire workshop
  </td>
  <td>
    <b>LDAR 399</b> — Resume/Portfolio Seminar: Professional portfolio curation, resume development, CLARB licensure pathway planning<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 442</b> — Design in Practice: Firm management, contract law, professional liability, LARE exam preparation modules with practice vignettes<br><br>
    <b>LDAR 448</b> — Capstone Project: Portfolio-ready body of work suitable for professional exhibition<br><br>
    Register for LARE exam sections; develop post-graduation licensure action plan
  </td>
</tr>
</table>

