<h2>SECTION 5 | ADVISOR NOTES &amp; ADDITIONAL RESOURCES</h2>

<h3>Relevant Student Organizations</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:100%;" colspan="2">
• <b>ASLA Student Chapter</b> — American Society of Landscape Architects (primary professional organization; competitions, networking, mentorship)<br>
• <b>NOMA Student Chapter</b> — National Organization of Minority Architects (cross-disciplinary design community)<br>
• <b>CAES Ambassadors</b> — College-level student leadership and recruitment team<br>
• <b>Sigma Lambda Alpha</b> — Landscape Architecture Honor Society (by invitation, based on GPA and professional engagement)<br>
• <b>Engineers Without Borders</b> — Cross-disciplinary community design and infrastructure projects<br>
• <b>1891 Student Organizations</b> — University-wide registry of 200+ clubs, Greek organizations, and honor societies
</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Scholarships &amp; Funding Opportunities</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:100%;" colspan="2">
• <b>ASLA Student Awards</b> — National design competition with cash prizes and portfolio recognition<br>
• <b>LAF (Landscape Architecture Foundation) Scholarships</b> — Multiple merit- and need-based scholarships for LA students<br>
• <b>CAES Dean's Scholarship</b> — College-level merit scholarship for CAES majors<br>
• <b>NC A&amp;T Foundation Scholarships</b> — University-wide endowed scholarships (apply through Aggie Access by March 1)<br>
• <b>Diversity Advancement Scholarships</b> — ASLA and allied organizations offer scholarships supporting underrepresented students in landscape architecture<br>
• <b>USDA/NIFA Scholarships</b> — Federal funding opportunities for students in agriculture and environmental sciences
</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Key Deadlines / Milestones</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:35%;">Freshman Fall</td><td>Declare LA major by end of first semester; enroll in LDAR 103 + 147 + 170</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sophomore Spring</td><td>Complete all 100-level LDAR courses before advancing to 200-level studios</td></tr>
<tr><td>Any Summer</td><td>LDAR 400 — Internship Independent Study (can be taken any summer once a position is secured)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Senior Fall</td><td>Complete LDAR 399 portfolio/resume seminar; submit capstone proposal; LDAR 440, 447, 455</td></tr>
<tr><td>Senior Spring</td><td>Capstone exhibition and jury review (LDAR 448); file CLARB exam application</td></tr>
<tr><td>Post-Graduation</td><td>Begin LARE exam sequence (most states allow testing upon degree completion)</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Additional Information</h3>
<table class="form-table">
<tr><td style="width:100%;" colspan="2">
• The BSLA is a <b>professional degree</b> — graduates are eligible for LARE exam and professional licensure without requiring a graduate degree.<br>
• NC A&amp;T's program uniquely emphasizes <b>environmental justice and community-engaged design</b> as a core thread, not an elective add-on.<br>
• The new Fall 2026 curriculum features <b>24 sequenced LDAR courses</b> organized across 4 years: 7 courses (Year 1 Explore), 6 courses (Year 2 Engage), 4 courses (Year 3 Develop), 7 courses (Year 4 Launch).<br>
• Students should maintain a <b>portfolio from Day 1</b> — all studios produce portfolio-ready work; LDAR 399 provides formal portfolio curation in senior year.<br>
• The program supports the <b>EMMA (Experiential Major Mapping Assistant)</b> digital platform for tracking milestone completion, career outlook, and credential validation progress.
</td></tr>
</table>

